4.Name: Web Server No 404 Error Code Check
4.Synopsis: The remote web server does not return 404 error codes.
4.Description:
The remote web server is configured such that it does not return '404
Not Found' error codes when a nonexistent file is requested, perhaps
returning instead a site map, search page or authentication page.

Nessus has enabled some counter measures for this.  However, they
might be insufficient.  If a great number of security holes are
produced for this port, they might not all be accurate.
4.Plugin Output:
CGI scanning will be disabled for this host because the host responds
to requests for non-existent URLs with HTTP code 302
rather than 404. The requested URL was : 

    http://10.1.0.10:8008/4Xja1CT4lAHL.html

9.Name: Nessus SYN scanner
9.Synopsis: It is possible to determine which TCP ports are open.
9.Description:
This plugin is a SYN 'half-open' port scanner.  It shall be reasonably
quick even against a firewalled target. 

Note that SYN scans are less intrusive than TCP (full connect) scans
against broken services, but they might cause problems for less robust
firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.
9.Solution: Protect your target with an IP filter.
9.Plugin Output: Port 22/tcp was found to be open

  - The version of the Nessus Engine.
  - The port scanner(s) used.
  - The port range scanned.
  - The ping round trip time 
  - Whether credentialed or third-party patch management
    checks are possible.
  - Whether the display of superseded patches is enabled
  - The date of the scan.
  - The duration of the scan.
  - The number of hosts scanned in parallel.
  - The number of checks done in parallel.

37.Name: HTTP Methods Allowed (per directory)
37.Synopsis:
This plugin determines which HTTP methods are allowed on various CGI
directories.
37.Description:
By calling the OPTIONS method, it is possible to determine which HTTP
methods are allowed on each directory.

The following HTTP methods are considered insecure:
  PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, TRACE, HEAD

Many frameworks and languages treat 'HEAD' as a 'GET' request, albeit
one without any body in the response. If a security constraint was
set on 'GET' requests such that only 'authenticatedUsers' could
access GET requests for a particular servlet or resource, it would be
bypassed for the 'HEAD' version. This allowed unauthorized blind
submission of any privileged GET request.

As this list may be incomplete, the plugin also tests - if 'Thorough
tests' are enabled or 'Enable web applications tests' is set to 'yes'
in the scan policy - various known HTTP methods on each directory and
considers them as unsupported if it receives a response code of 400,
403, 405, or 501.

Note that the plugin output is only informational and does not
necessarily indicate the presence of any security vulnerabilities.
37.Plugin Output:
Based on the response to an OPTIONS request :

  - HTTP methods GET HEAD OPTIONS POST are allowed on : 

    /

42.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
42.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
42.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :

  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.

  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.

  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.

If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
42.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.

chain sent by the remote host, but it is signed by an unknown
certificate authority :

are known to be vulnerable to collision attacks. An attacker can
exploit this to generate another certificate with the same digital
signature, allowing the attacker to masquerade as the affected
service.

Note that this plugin reports all SSL certificate chains signed with
SHA-1 that expire after January 1, 2017 as vulnerable. This is in
accordance with Google's gradual sunsetting of the SHA-1 cryptographic
hash algorithm.

Note that this plugin will only fire on root certificates that are known certificate authorities as listed in Tenable
Community Knowledge Article 000001752. That is what differentiates this plugin from plugin 35291, which will fire on
any certificate, not just known certificate authority root certificates.

Known certificate authority root certificates are inherently trusted and so any potential issues with the signature,
including it being signed using a weak hashing algorithm, are not considered security issues.
54.Solution: Contact the Certificate Authority to have the certificate reissued.

55.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
55.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
55.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.

As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.

PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
55.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
55.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

56.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
56.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
56.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.

Please note the following :

- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.

- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.

86.Name: HTTP Methods Allowed (per directory)
86.Synopsis:
This plugin determines which HTTP methods are allowed on various CGI
directories.
86.Description:
By calling the OPTIONS method, it is possible to determine which HTTP
methods are allowed on each directory.

The following HTTP methods are considered insecure:
  PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, TRACE, HEAD

Many frameworks and languages treat 'HEAD' as a 'GET' request, albeit
one without any body in the response. If a security constraint was
set on 'GET' requests such that only 'authenticatedUsers' could
access GET requests for a particular servlet or resource, it would be
bypassed for the 'HEAD' version. This allowed unauthorized blind
submission of any privileged GET request.

As this list may be incomplete, the plugin also tests - if 'Thorough
tests' are enabled or 'Enable web applications tests' is set to 'yes'
in the scan policy - various known HTTP methods on each directory and
considers them as unsupported if it receives a response code of 400,
403, 405, or 501.

Note that the plugin output is only informational and does not
necessarily indicate the presence of any security vulnerabilities.

90.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
90.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
90.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :

  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.

  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.

  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.

If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
90.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.

99.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
99.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
99.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.

As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.

PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
99.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
99.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

authenticated encryption modes such as GCM cannot be used with

and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.

130.Name: HTTP Methods Allowed (per directory)
130.Synopsis:
This plugin determines which HTTP methods are allowed on various CGI
directories.
130.Description:
By calling the OPTIONS method, it is possible to determine which HTTP
methods are allowed on each directory.

The following HTTP methods are considered insecure:
  PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, TRACE, HEAD

Many frameworks and languages treat 'HEAD' as a 'GET' request, albeit
one without any body in the response. If a security constraint was
set on 'GET' requests such that only 'authenticatedUsers' could
access GET requests for a particular servlet or resource, it would be
bypassed for the 'HEAD' version. This allowed unauthorized blind
submission of any privileged GET request.

As this list may be incomplete, the plugin also tests - if 'Thorough
tests' are enabled or 'Enable web applications tests' is set to 'yes'
in the scan policy - various known HTTP methods on each directory and
considers them as unsupported if it receives a response code of 400,
403, 405, or 501.

Note that the plugin output is only informational and does not
necessarily indicate the presence of any security vulnerabilities.

133.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
133.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
133.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :

  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.

  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.

  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.

If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
133.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.

chain sent by the remote host, but it is signed by an unknown
certificate authority :

139.Name: HSTS Missing From HTTPS Server
139.Synopsis: The remote web server is not enforcing HSTS.
139.Description:
The remote HTTPS server is not enforcing HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS). 
HSTS is an optional response header that can be configured on the server to instruct 
the browser to only communicate via HTTPS. The lack of HSTS allows downgrade attacks,
SSL-stripping man-in-the-middle attacks, and weakens cookie-hijacking protections.
139.Solution: Configure the remote web server to use HSTS.
139.Plugin Output:
The remote HTTPS server does not send the HTTP
  "Strict-Transport-Security" header.

140.Name: Apache Server ETag Header Information Disclosure
140.Synopsis:
The remote web server is affected by an information disclosure
vulnerability.
140.Description:
The remote web server is affected by an information disclosure
vulnerability due to the ETag header providing sensitive information
that could aid an attacker, such as the inode number of requested
files.
140.Solution:
Modify the HTTP ETag header of the web server to not include file
inodes in the ETag header calculation. Refer to the linked Apache
documentation for more information.

142.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
142.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
142.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.

As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.

PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
142.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
142.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

143.Name: TLS Version 1.1 Protocol Detection
143.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
143.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.1.
TLS 1.1 lacks support for current and recommended cipher suites.
Ciphers that support encryption before MAC computation, and
authenticated encryption modes such as GCM cannot be used with
TLS 1.1

As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that are not enabled for TLS 1.2 
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
143.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and/or 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.1.
143.Plugin Output: TLSv1.1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

173.Name: HTTP Methods Allowed (per directory)
173.Synopsis:
This plugin determines which HTTP methods are allowed on various CGI
directories.
173.Description:
By calling the OPTIONS method, it is possible to determine which HTTP
methods are allowed on each directory.

The following HTTP methods are considered insecure:
  PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, TRACE, HEAD

Many frameworks and languages treat 'HEAD' as a 'GET' request, albeit
one without any body in the response. If a security constraint was
set on 'GET' requests such that only 'authenticatedUsers' could
access GET requests for a particular servlet or resource, it would be
bypassed for the 'HEAD' version. This allowed unauthorized blind
submission of any privileged GET request.

As this list may be incomplete, the plugin also tests - if 'Thorough
tests' are enabled or 'Enable web applications tests' is set to 'yes'
in the scan policy - various known HTTP methods on each directory and
considers them as unsupported if it receives a response code of 400,
403, 405, or 501.

Note that the plugin output is only informational and does not
necessarily indicate the presence of any security vulnerabilities.

176.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
176.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
176.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :

  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.

  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.

  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.

If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
176.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.

183.Name: HSTS Missing From HTTPS Server
183.Synopsis: The remote web server is not enforcing HSTS.
183.Description:
The remote HTTPS server is not enforcing HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS). 
HSTS is an optional response header that can be configured on the server to instruct 
the browser to only communicate via HTTPS. The lack of HSTS allows downgrade attacks,
SSL-stripping man-in-the-middle attacks, and weakens cookie-hijacking protections.
183.Solution: Configure the remote web server to use HSTS.

185.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
185.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
185.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.

As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.

PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
185.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
185.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

186.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
186.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
186.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.

Please note the following :

- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.

- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
186.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

188.Name: TLS Version 1.1 Protocol Detection
188.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
188.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.1.
TLS 1.1 lacks support for current and recommended cipher suites.
Ciphers that support encryption before MAC computation, and
authenticated encryption modes such as GCM cannot be used with
TLS 1.1

As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that are not enabled for TLS 1.2 
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
188.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and/or 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.1.

211.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
211.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
211.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :

  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.

  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.

  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.

If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
211.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.

219.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
219.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
219.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.

As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.

PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
219.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
219.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

220.Name: TLS Version 1.1 Protocol Detection
220.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
220.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.1.
TLS 1.1 lacks support for current and recommended cipher suites.
Ciphers that support encryption before MAC computation, and
authenticated encryption modes such as GCM cannot be used with
TLS 1.1

As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that are not enabled for TLS 1.2 
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
220.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and/or 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.1.
220.Plugin Output: TLSv1.1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

228.Name: Web Server No 404 Error Code Check
228.Synopsis: The remote web server does not return 404 error codes.
228.Description:
The remote web server is configured such that it does not return '404
Not Found' error codes when a nonexistent file is requested, perhaps
returning instead a site map, search page or authentication page.

Nessus has enabled some counter measures for this.  However, they
might be insufficient.  If a great number of security holes are
produced for this port, they might not all be accurate.

234.Name: Nessus SYN scanner
234.Synopsis: It is possible to determine which TCP ports are open.
234.Description:
This plugin is a SYN 'half-open' port scanner.  It shall be reasonably
quick even against a firewalled target. 

Note that SYN scans are less intrusive than TCP (full connect) scans
against broken services, but they might cause problems for less robust
firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.
234.Solution: Protect your target with an IP filter.

266.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
266.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
266.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :

  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.

  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.

  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.

If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
266.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.

278.Name: SSL Certificate Signed Using Weak Hashing Algorithm (Known CA)
278.Synopsis:
A known CA SSL certificate in the certificate chain has been signed
using a weak hashing algorithm.
278.Description:
The remote service uses a known CA certificate in the SSL certificate
chain that has been signed using a cryptographically weak hashing
algorithm (e.g., MD2, MD4, MD5, or SHA1). These signature algorithms
are known to be vulnerable to collision attacks. An attacker can
exploit this to generate another certificate with the same digital
signature, allowing the attacker to masquerade as the affected
service.

Note that this plugin reports all SSL certificate chains signed with
SHA-1 that expire after January 1, 2017 as vulnerable. This is in
accordance with Google's gradual sunsetting of the SHA-1 cryptographic
hash algorithm.

Note that this plugin will only fire on root certificates that are known certificate authorities as listed in Tenable
Community Knowledge Article 000001752. That is what differentiates this plugin from plugin 35291, which will fire on
any certificate, not just known certificate authority root certificates.

Known certificate authority root certificates are inherently trusted and so any potential issues with the signature,
including it being signed using a weak hashing algorithm, are not considered security issues.
278.Solution: Contact the Certificate Authority to have the certificate reissued.

283.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
283.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
283.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.

As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.

PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
283.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
283.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

284.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
284.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
284.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.

Please note the following :

- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.

- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
284.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

285.Name: OS Security Patch Assessment Not Available
285.Synopsis: OS Security Patch Assessment is not available.
285.Description:
OS Security Patch Assessment is not available on the remote host.
This does not necessarily indicate a problem with the scan.
Credentials may not have been provided, OS security patch assessment
may not be supported for the target, the target may not have been
identified, or another issue may have occurred that prevented OS
security patch assessment from being available. See plugin output for
details.

This plugin reports non-failure information impacting the availability
of OS Security Patch Assessment. Failure information is reported by
plugin 21745 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment failed'.  If a target
host is not supported for OS Security Patch Assessment, plugin
110695 : 'OS Security Patch Assessment Checks Not Supported' will
report concurrently with this plugin.

286.Name: TLS Version 1.1 Protocol Detection
286.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
286.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.1.
TLS 1.1 lacks support for current and recommended cipher suites.
Ciphers that support encryption before MAC computation, and
authenticated encryption modes such as GCM cannot be used with
TLS 1.1

As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that are not enabled for TLS 1.2 
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
286.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and/or 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.1.
286.Plugin Output: TLSv1.1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

289.Name: HSTS Missing From HTTPS Server (RFC 6797)
289.Synopsis: The remote web server is not enforcing HSTS, as defined by RFC 6797.
289.Description:
The remote web server is not enforcing HSTS, as defined by RFC 6797. 
HSTS is an optional response header that can be configured on the server to instruct 
the browser to only communicate via HTTPS. The lack of HSTS allows downgrade attacks,
SSL-stripping man-in-the-middle attacks, and weakens cookie-hijacking protections.
289.Solution: Configure the remote web server to use HSTS.

The remote HTTPS server does not send the HTTP
  "Strict-Transport-Security" header.

291.Synopsis: The remote host advertises discouraged SSL/TLS ciphers.

  - 0x13,0x02 TLS_AES_256_GCM_SHA384
  - 0x13,0x03 TLS_CHACHA20_POLY1305_SHA256

TLSv1.2:
  - 0xC0,0x2B ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256
  - 0xC0,0x2F ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256
  - 0xC0,0x2C ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384

  - 0x00,0x9F DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384

nearly every client released in the last five (or more) years.

328.Name: HTTP Methods Allowed (per directory)
328.Synopsis:
This plugin determines which HTTP methods are allowed on various CGI
directories.
328.Description:
By calling the OPTIONS method, it is possible to determine which HTTP
methods are allowed on each directory.

The following HTTP methods are considered insecure:
  PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, TRACE, HEAD

Many frameworks and languages treat 'HEAD' as a 'GET' request, albeit
one without any body in the response. If a security constraint was
set on 'GET' requests such that only 'authenticatedUsers' could
access GET requests for a particular servlet or resource, it would be
bypassed for the 'HEAD' version. This allowed unauthorized blind
submission of any privileged GET request.

As this list may be incomplete, the plugin also tests - if 'Thorough
tests' are enabled or 'Enable web applications tests' is set to 'yes'
in the scan policy - various known HTTP methods on each directory and
considers them as unsupported if it receives a response code of 400,
403, 405, or 501.

Note that the plugin output is only informational and does not
necessarily indicate the presence of any security vulnerabilities.
328.Plugin Output:
Based on the response to an OPTIONS request :

  - HTTP methods GET HEAD HEAD HEAD OPTIONS POST are allowed on : 

    /

333.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
333.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
333.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :

  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.

  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.

  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.

346.Name: SSL Certificate Signed Using Weak Hashing Algorithm (Known CA)
346.Synopsis:
A known CA SSL certificate in the certificate chain has been signed
using a weak hashing algorithm.
346.Description:
The remote service uses a known CA certificate in the SSL certificate
chain that has been signed using a cryptographically weak hashing
algorithm (e.g., MD2, MD4, MD5, or SHA1). These signature algorithms
are known to be vulnerable to collision attacks. An attacker can
exploit this to generate another certificate with the same digital
signature, allowing the attacker to masquerade as the affected
service.

Note that this plugin reports all SSL certificate chains signed with
SHA-1 that expire after January 1, 2017 as vulnerable. This is in
accordance with Google's gradual sunsetting of the SHA-1 cryptographic
hash algorithm.

Note that this plugin will only fire on root certificates that are known certificate authorities as listed in Tenable
Community Knowledge Article 000001752. That is what differentiates this plugin from plugin 35291, which will fire on
any certificate, not just known certificate authority root certificates.

Known certificate authority root certificates are inherently trusted and so any potential issues with the signature,
including it being signed using a weak hashing algorithm, are not considered security issues.
346.Solution: Contact the Certificate Authority to have the certificate reissued.

347.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
347.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
347.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.

As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.

PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
347.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
347.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

348.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
348.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
348.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.

Please note the following :

- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.

- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.

SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

365.Name: Windows Terminal Services Enabled
365.Synopsis: The remote Windows host has Terminal Services enabled.
365.Description:
Terminal Services allows a Windows user to remotely obtain a graphical
login (and therefore act as a local user on the remote host).

If an attacker gains a valid login and password, this service could be
used to gain further access on the remote host.  An attacker may also
use this service to mount a dictionary attack against the remote host
to try to log in remotely.

Note that RDP (the Remote Desktop Protocol) is vulnerable to
Man-in-the-middle attacks, making it easy for attackers to steal the
credentials of legitimate users by impersonating the Windows server.
365.Solution:
Disable Terminal Services if you do not use it, and do not allow this
service to run across the Internet.

366.Name: Nessus SYN scanner
366.Synopsis: It is possible to determine which TCP ports are open.
366.Description:
This plugin is a SYN 'half-open' port scanner.  It shall be reasonably
quick even against a firewalled target. 

Note that SYN scans are less intrusive than TCP (full connect) scans
against broken services, but they might cause problems for less robust
firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.
366.Solution: Protect your target with an IP filter.
366.Plugin Output: Port 21/tcp was found to be open

392.Name: HTTP Methods Allowed (per directory)
392.Synopsis:
This plugin determines which HTTP methods are allowed on various CGI
directories.
392.Description:
By calling the OPTIONS method, it is possible to determine which HTTP
methods are allowed on each directory.

The following HTTP methods are considered insecure:
  PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, TRACE, HEAD

Many frameworks and languages treat 'HEAD' as a 'GET' request, albeit
one without any body in the response. If a security constraint was
set on 'GET' requests such that only 'authenticatedUsers' could
access GET requests for a particular servlet or resource, it would be
bypassed for the 'HEAD' version. This allowed unauthorized blind
submission of any privileged GET request.

As this list may be incomplete, the plugin also tests - if 'Thorough
tests' are enabled or 'Enable web applications tests' is set to 'yes'
in the scan policy - various known HTTP methods on each directory and
considers them as unsupported if it receives a response code of 400,
403, 405, or 501.

Note that the plugin output is only informational and does not
necessarily indicate the presence of any security vulnerabilities.

Based on the response to an OPTIONS request :

    /

395.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
395.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
395.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :

  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.

  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.

  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.

If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
395.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.
395.Plugin Output:
The following certificate was at the top of the certificate
chain sent by the remote host, but it is signed by an unknown
certificate authority :

|-Subject : CN=Lib-App-Win2016.sac.local
|-Issuer  : CN=Lib-App-Win2016.sac.local

405.Name: HSTS Missing From HTTPS Server
405.Synopsis: The remote web server is not enforcing HSTS.

405.Solution: Configure the remote web server to use HSTS.

408.Name: SSL Certificate Signed Using Weak Hashing Algorithm (Known CA)
408.Synopsis:
A known CA SSL certificate in the certificate chain has been signed
using a weak hashing algorithm.
408.Description:
The remote service uses a known CA certificate in the SSL certificate
chain that has been signed using a cryptographically weak hashing
algorithm (e.g., MD2, MD4, MD5, or SHA1). These signature algorithms
are known to be vulnerable to collision attacks. An attacker can
exploit this to generate another certificate with the same digital
signature, allowing the attacker to masquerade as the affected
service.

Note that this plugin reports all SSL certificate chains signed with
SHA-1 that expire after January 1, 2017 as vulnerable. This is in
accordance with Google's gradual sunsetting of the SHA-1 cryptographic
hash algorithm.

Note that this plugin will only fire on root certificates that are known certificate authorities as listed in Tenable
Community Knowledge Article 000001752. That is what differentiates this plugin from plugin 35291, which will fire on
any certificate, not just known certificate authority root certificates.

Known certificate authority root certificates are inherently trusted and so any potential issues with the signature,
including it being signed using a weak hashing algorithm, are not considered security issues.
408.Solution: Contact the Certificate Authority to have the certificate reissued.
408.Plugin Output:
The following known CA certificates were part of the certificate
chain sent by the remote host, but contain hashes that are considered

409.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
409.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
409.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.

As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.

PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
409.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
409.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

410.Name: TLS Version 1.1 Protocol Detection
410.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
410.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.1.
TLS 1.1 lacks support for current and recommended cipher suites.
Ciphers that support encryption before MAC computation, and
authenticated encryption modes such as GCM cannot be used with
TLS 1.1

As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that are not enabled for TLS 1.2 
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
410.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and/or 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.1.
410.Plugin Output: TLSv1.1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

411.Name: TLS Version 1.2 Protocol Detection
411.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using a version of TLS.
411.Description: The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.2.
411.Plugin Output: TLSv1.2 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

412.Name: HSTS Missing From HTTPS Server (RFC 6797)
412.Synopsis: The remote web server is not enforcing HSTS, as defined by RFC 6797.
412.Description:
The remote web server is not enforcing HSTS, as defined by RFC 6797. 
HSTS is an optional response header that can be configured on the server to instruct 
the browser to only communicate via HTTPS. The lack of HSTS allows downgrade attacks,
SSL-stripping man-in-the-middle attacks, and weakens cookie-hijacking protections.
412.Solution: Configure the remote web server to use HSTS.
412.Plugin Output:
The remote HTTPS server does not send the HTTP
  "Strict-Transport-Security" header.

413.Name: SSL/TLS Recommended Cipher Suites
413.Synopsis: The remote host advertises discouraged SSL/TLS ciphers.
413.Description:
The remote host has open SSL/TLS ports which advertise discouraged cipher suites. It is recommended to only enable
support for the following cipher suites:

TLSv1.3:
  - 0x13,0x01 TLS_AES_128_GCM_SHA256
  - 0x13,0x02 TLS_AES_256_GCM_SHA384
  - 0x13,0x03 TLS_CHACHA20_POLY1305_SHA256

TLSv1.2:
  - 0xC0,0x2B ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256
  - 0xC0,0x2F ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256
  - 0xC0,0x2C ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384
  - 0xC0,0x30 ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384
  - 0xCC,0xA9 ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305
  - 0xCC,0xA8 ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305
  - 0x00,0x9E DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256
  - 0x00,0x9F DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384

This is the recommended configuration for the vast majority of services, as it is highly secure and compatible with
nearly every client released in the last five (or more) years.
413.Solution: Only enable support for recommened cipher suites.

446.Name: Strict Transport Security (STS) Detection
446.Synopsis: The remote web server implements Strict Transport Security.
446.Description:
The remote web server implements Strict Transport Security (STS).
The goal of STS is to make sure that a user does not accidentally
downgrade the security of his or her browser.

All unencrypted HTTP connections are redirected to HTTPS.  The browser
is expected to treat all cookies as 'secure' and to close the
connection in the event of potentially insecure situations.

450.Name: HTTP Methods Allowed (per directory)
450.Synopsis:
This plugin determines which HTTP methods are allowed on various CGI
directories.
450.Description:
By calling the OPTIONS method, it is possible to determine which HTTP
methods are allowed on each directory.

The following HTTP methods are considered insecure:
  PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, TRACE, HEAD

Many frameworks and languages treat 'HEAD' as a 'GET' request, albeit
one without any body in the response. If a security constraint was
set on 'GET' requests such that only 'authenticatedUsers' could
access GET requests for a particular servlet or resource, it would be
bypassed for the 'HEAD' version. This allowed unauthorized blind
submission of any privileged GET request.

As this list may be incomplete, the plugin also tests - if 'Thorough
tests' are enabled or 'Enable web applications tests' is set to 'yes'
in the scan policy - various known HTTP methods on each directory and
considers them as unsupported if it receives a response code of 400,
403, 405, or 501.

Note that the plugin output is only informational and does not
necessarily indicate the presence of any security vulnerabilities.
450.Plugin Output:
Based on the response to an OPTIONS request :

  - HTTP methods GET HEAD HEAD HEAD OPTIONS POST are allowed on : 

    /

455.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
455.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
455.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :

  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.

  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.

  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.

If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
455.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.
455.Plugin Output:
The following certificate was at the top of the certificate
chain sent by the remote host, but it is signed by an unknown
certificate authority :

468.Name: SSL Certificate Signed Using Weak Hashing Algorithm (Known CA)
468.Synopsis:
A known CA SSL certificate in the certificate chain has been signed
using a weak hashing algorithm.
468.Description:
The remote service uses a known CA certificate in the SSL certificate
chain that has been signed using a cryptographically weak hashing
algorithm (e.g., MD2, MD4, MD5, or SHA1). These signature algorithms
are known to be vulnerable to collision attacks. An attacker can
exploit this to generate another certificate with the same digital
signature, allowing the attacker to masquerade as the affected
service.

Note that this plugin reports all SSL certificate chains signed with
SHA-1 that expire after January 1, 2017 as vulnerable. This is in
accordance with Google's gradual sunsetting of the SHA-1 cryptographic
hash algorithm.

Note that this plugin will only fire on root certificates that are known certificate authorities as listed in Tenable
Community Knowledge Article 000001752. That is what differentiates this plugin from plugin 35291, which will fire on
any certificate, not just known certificate authority root certificates.

Known certificate authority root certificates are inherently trusted and so any potential issues with the signature,
including it being signed using a weak hashing algorithm, are not considered security issues.
468.Solution: Contact the Certificate Authority to have the certificate reissued.

469.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
469.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
469.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.

As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.

PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
469.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
469.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

470.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
470.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
470.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.

Please note the following :

- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.

- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.
470.Plugin Output:
SSH was detected on port 22 but no credentials were provided.
SSH local checks were not enabled.

472.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
472.Description:

TLS 1.1 lacks support for current and recommended cipher suites.
Ciphers that support encryption before MAC computation, and
authenticated encryption modes such as GCM cannot be used with
TLS 1.1

and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.

487.Synopsis: It is possible to determine which TCP ports are open.

quick even against a firewalled target.

against broken services, but they might cause problems for less robust
firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.

The remote IP address seems to connect to different hosts

Reverse NAT is a technology which lets multiple computers offer
public services on different ports via the same IP address. 

Based on OS fingerprinting results, it seems that different 
operating systems are listening on different remote ports.

Note that this behavior may also indicate the presence of a
intercepting proxy, a load balancer or a traffic shaper.

downgrade the security of his or her browser.

is expected to treat all cookies as 'secure' and to close the
connection in the event of potentially insecure situations.

512.Name: HTTP Methods Allowed (per directory)
512.Synopsis:
This plugin determines which HTTP methods are allowed on various CGI
directories.
512.Description:
By calling the OPTIONS method, it is possible to determine which HTTP
methods are allowed on each directory.

The following HTTP methods are considered insecure:
  PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, TRACE, HEAD

Many frameworks and languages treat 'HEAD' as a 'GET' request, albeit
one without any body in the response. If a security constraint was
set on 'GET' requests such that only 'authenticatedUsers' could
access GET requests for a particular servlet or resource, it would be
bypassed for the 'HEAD' version. This allowed unauthorized blind
submission of any privileged GET request.

As this list may be incomplete, the plugin also tests - if 'Thorough
tests' are enabled or 'Enable web applications tests' is set to 'yes'
in the scan policy - various known HTTP methods on each directory and
considers them as unsupported if it receives a response code of 400,
403, 405, or 501.

Note that the plugin output is only informational and does not
necessarily indicate the presence of any security vulnerabilities.

513.Name: HTTP Methods Allowed (per directory)
513.Synopsis:
This plugin determines which HTTP methods are allowed on various CGI
directories.
513.Description:
By calling the OPTIONS method, it is possible to determine which HTTP
methods are allowed on each directory.

The following HTTP methods are considered insecure:
  PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, TRACE, HEAD

Many frameworks and languages treat 'HEAD' as a 'GET' request, albeit
one without any body in the response. If a security constraint was
set on 'GET' requests such that only 'authenticatedUsers' could
access GET requests for a particular servlet or resource, it would be
bypassed for the 'HEAD' version. This allowed unauthorized blind
submission of any privileged GET request.

As this list may be incomplete, the plugin also tests - if 'Thorough
tests' are enabled or 'Enable web applications tests' is set to 'yes'
in the scan policy - various known HTTP methods on each directory and
considers them as unsupported if it receives a response code of 400,
403, 405, or 501.

Note that the plugin output is only informational and does not
necessarily indicate the presence of any security vulnerabilities.
513.Plugin Output:
Based on the response to an OPTIONS request :

  - HTTP methods GET HEAD OPTIONS POST are allowed on : 

    /

517.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
517.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
517.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :

  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.

  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.

  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.

If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
517.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.

530.Name: SSL Certificate Signed Using Weak Hashing Algorithm (Known CA)
530.Synopsis:
A known CA SSL certificate in the certificate chain has been signed
using a weak hashing algorithm.
530.Description:
The remote service uses a known CA certificate in the SSL certificate
chain that has been signed using a cryptographically weak hashing
algorithm (e.g., MD2, MD4, MD5, or SHA1). These signature algorithms
are known to be vulnerable to collision attacks. An attacker can
exploit this to generate another certificate with the same digital
signature, allowing the attacker to masquerade as the affected
service.

Note that this plugin reports all SSL certificate chains signed with
SHA-1 that expire after January 1, 2017 as vulnerable. This is in
accordance with Google's gradual sunsetting of the SHA-1 cryptographic
hash algorithm.

Note that this plugin will only fire on root certificates that are known certificate authorities as listed in Tenable
Community Knowledge Article 000001752. That is what differentiates this plugin from plugin 35291, which will fire on
any certificate, not just known certificate authority root certificates.

Known certificate authority root certificates are inherently trusted and so any potential issues with the signature,
including it being signed using a weak hashing algorithm, are not considered security issues.
530.Solution: Contact the Certificate Authority to have the certificate reissued.

531.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
531.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
531.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.

As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.

PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
531.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
531.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

532.Name: Target Credential Status by Authentication Protocol - No Credentials Provided
532.Synopsis:
Nessus was able to find common ports used for local checks,
however, no credentials were provided in the scan policy.
532.Description:
Nessus was not able to successfully authenticate directly to the
remote target on an available authentication protocol. Nessus was
able to connect to the remote port and identify that the service
running on the port supports an authentication protocol, but Nessus
failed to authenticate to the remote service using the provided
credentials. There may have been a protocol failure that prevented
authentication from being attempted or all of the provided credentials
for the authentication protocol may be invalid. See plugin output for
error details.

Please note the following :

- This plugin reports per protocol, so it is possible for
  valid credentials to be provided for one protocol and not
  another. For example, authentication may succeed via SSH
  but fail via SMB, while no credentials were provided for
  an available SNMP service.

- Providing valid credentials for all available
  authentication protocols may improve scan coverage, but
  the value of successful authentication for a given
  protocol may vary from target to target depending upon
  what data (if any) is gathered from the target via that
  protocol. For example, successful authentication via SSH
  is more valuable for Linux targets than for Windows
  targets, and likewise successful authentication via SMB
  is more valuable for Windows targets than for Linux
  targets.

554.Name: DNS Server Cache Snooping Remote Information Disclosure
554.Synopsis: The remote DNS server is vulnerable to cache snooping attacks.
554.Description:
The remote DNS server responds to queries for third-party domains
that do not have the recursion bit set. 

This may allow a remote attacker to determine which domains have
recently been resolved via this name server, and therefore which hosts
have been recently visited. 

For instance, if an attacker was interested in whether your company
utilizes the online services of a particular financial institution,
they would be able to use this attack to build a statistical model
regarding company usage of that financial institution.  Of course, the
attack can also be used to find B2B partners, web-surfing patterns,
external mail servers, and more.

Note: If this is an internal DNS server not accessible to outside
networks, attacks would be limited to the internal network. This
may include employees, consultants and potentially users on
a guest network or WiFi connection if supported.
554.Solution: Contact the vendor of the DNS software for a fix.

567.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
567.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
567.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :

  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.

  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.

  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.

If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
567.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.

576.Name: TLS Version 1.0 Protocol Detection
576.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
576.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 has a
number of cryptographic design flaws. Modern implementations of TLS 1.0
mitigate these problems, but newer versions of TLS like 1.2 and 1.3 are
designed against these flaws and should be used whenever possible.

As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that aren’t enabled for TLS 1.2
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.

PCI DSS v3.2 requires that TLS 1.0 be disabled entirely by June 30,
2018, except for POS POI terminals (and the SSL/TLS termination
points to which they connect) that can be verified as not being
susceptible to any known exploits.
576.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.0.
576.Plugin Output: TLSv1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

577.Name: TLS Version 1.1 Protocol Detection
577.Synopsis: The remote service encrypts traffic using an older version of TLS.
577.Description:
The remote service accepts connections encrypted using TLS 1.1.
TLS 1.1 lacks support for current and recommended cipher suites.
Ciphers that support encryption before MAC computation, and
authenticated encryption modes such as GCM cannot be used with
TLS 1.1

As of March 31, 2020, Endpoints that are not enabled for TLS 1.2 
and higher will no longer function properly with major web browsers and major vendors.
577.Solution: Enable support for TLS 1.2 and/or 1.3, and disable support for TLS 1.1.
577.Plugin Output: TLSv1.1 is enabled and the server supports at least one cipher.

quick even against a firewalled target.

against broken services, but they might cause problems for less robust
firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.

625.Name: SSL Certificate Cannot Be Trusted
625.Synopsis: The SSL certificate for this service cannot be trusted.
625.Description:
The server's X.509 certificate cannot be trusted. This situation can
occur in three different ways, in which the chain of trust can be
broken, as stated below :

  - First, the top of the certificate chain sent by the
    server might not be descended from a known public
    certificate authority. This can occur either when the
    top of the chain is an unrecognized, self-signed
    certificate, or when intermediate certificates are
    missing that would connect the top of the certificate
    chain to a known public certificate authority.

  - Second, the certificate chain may contain a certificate
    that is not valid at the time of the scan. This can
    occur either when the scan occurs before one of the
    certificate's 'notBefore' dates, or after one of the
    certificate's 'notAfter' dates.

  - Third, the certificate chain may contain a signature
    that either didn't match the certificate's information
    or could not be verified. Bad signatures can be fixed by
    getting the certificate with the bad signature to be
    re-signed by its issuer. Signatures that could not be
    verified are the result of the certificate's issuer
    using a signing algorithm that Nessus either does not
    support or does not recognize.

If the remote host is a public host in production, any break in the
chain makes it more difficult for users to verify the authenticity and 
identity of the web server. This could make it easier to carry out 
man-in-the-middle attacks against the remote host.
625.Solution: Purchase or generate a proper SSL certificate for this service.

639.Name: SSL Certificate Signed Using Weak Hashing Algorithm (Known CA)
639.Synopsis:
A known CA SSL certificate in the certificate chain has been signed
using a weak hashing algorithm.
639.Description:
The remote service uses a known CA certificate in the SSL certificate
chain that has been signed using a cryptographically weak hashing
algorithm (e.g., MD2, MD4, MD5, or SHA1). These signature algorithms
are known to be vulnerable to collision attacks. An attacker can
exploit this to generate another certificate with the same digital
signature, allowing the attacker to masquerade as the affected
service.

Note that this plugin reports all SSL certificate chains signed with
SHA-1 that expire after January 1, 2017 as vulnerable. This is in
accordance with Google's gradual sunsetting of the SHA-1 cryptographic
hash algorithm.

Note that this plugin will only fire on root certificates that are known certificate authorities as listed in Tenable
Community Knowledge Article 000001752. That is what differentiates this plugin from plugin 35291, which will fire on
any certificate, not just known certificate authority root certificates.

Known certificate authority root certificates are inherently trusted and so any potential issues with the signature,
including it being signed using a weak hashing algorithm, are not considered security issues.
639.Solution: Contact the Certificate Authority to have the certificate reissued.
